post_text: UPDATE for VOL part-time! We are currently adding part-time virtual courses to students' schedules. This process includes completion of the application by the student/family, approval of courses by zoned school counselor, assignment of teacher by VOL, course placed on schedule by VOL, teacher assigning the course to the student, and then the student can begin the course. The process takes at least a week, and we are experiencing longer than normal processing times due to the extremely high volume of part-time course requests. The courses are self-paced and do not follow the district semester start and end times. Students will be given ample time to work and will not be penalized for a late start. Our hard-working, dedicated teachers will work with students to develop a personalized pacing guide to meet student goals for successful completion. Thank you for your understanding.

post_text:
AdventHealth race car driver Ross Chastain made a special stop at AdventHealth Daytona Beach on his way to the Coke Zero Sugar 400 at Daytona International Speedway. The ‘Melon Man’ driver donated Melon Man masks to AdventHealth staff as part of a promotion Ross ran on his www.melonmanbrand.com merchandise site.

As the Official Healthcare Champion of Volusia County Schools, AdventHealth has donated those masks for VCS students who need them. School Board members Ruben Colon and Carl Persis, and Assistant Superintendent of Student Services Rose Roland accepted the mask donations during Chastain’s visit. Pictured from left are Colon, Roland, AdventHealth CEO Ed Noseworthy, Chastain, AdventHealth CFO Cory Domayer, AdventHealth COO David Weis, and Persis.

post_text:
Staggered Start for Kindergarten

As we continue to plan for the reopening in the fall of 2020-2021, we look forward to welcoming all students back to school. For students that return to school in the traditional brick and mortar setting, we are continually working to develop schedules and safety procedures in response to COVID-19 in alignment with CDC guidelines to include a Kindergarten Staggered Start.

As we plan for Kindergarten Staggered Start schedules, we will ensure the needs of our kindergarten parents, students and staff are being met. We are also planning for all schools to spend time with kindergarten students during the first week of school to build relationships, set clear procedures and expectations, practice routines for safety procedures and social distancing, morning arrival routines, special area transition, cafeteria, and dismissal procedures.

We will work with individual schools’ needs to ensure a smooth transition into the new school year for our kindergarten students.

post_text:
VCS High Schools Begin Fall Sports Team Conditioning in July

Beginning Monday, July 6, all Volusia County Schools high schools will begin fall sports team conditioning. Participants will be given a health screening and temperature check prior to each day’s activities. In addition, our schools will follow established CDC guidelines for health and safety, including no groups larger than 10 people, no use of locker rooms or showers (during Phase 1), and all students must bring their own water bottles and may not share.
All students participating in fall sports team conditioning must have a current FHSAA athletic physical, a current FHSAA consent and release form, and a Volusia County COVID-19 waiver. The forms are available in the schools’ athletic offices and on school websites under the athletic tab.

“I am deeply saddened by the tragic and senseless events that led to the death of George Floyd. I empathize with our black community and truly recognize that Black Lives Matter. My heart goes out to the Floyd family and all of those who are hurting right now. As Superintendent, I want you to know, we here at VCS stand in solidarity against injustice, racism, discrimination, and violence of any kind. Our top priority is to ensure that all students, community members, and staff feel safe and welcomed in our schools. I truly hope as a district and as a community, we can work together to confront racism honestly and strive for equality.”
-Dr. Scott Fritz/ Superintendent Volusia County Schools

Hello VCS Family,
Now more than ever, we want to make sure we provide every opportunity for students to have every minute possible to make up for lost learning from COVID-19.

In the Fall of 2020-2021, Volusia County Schools is planning to have all students start on the first day of school. This will ensure that all students are afforded the opportunity to participate in 180 days of school, in alignment with Florida Statutes.

If a staggered schedule is requested, we will work with each school on a case by case basis to ensure the needs of our kindergarten parents, students, and staff are being met.

We will work with individual school's needs to ensure a smooth transition.

Volusia County Schools is responsible for the content of this message. If you have any questions, please direct them to your individual schools.

post_text: We are so happy to have the talented artwork of our students showcased! #VolusiaStudentsCreate
shared_text:
MOAS
May 5 at 5:00 PM ·

Welcome to the virtual 48th Volusia Students Create Exhibition! Enjoy works by students throughout 58 public Volusia County Schools ranging from Kindergarten through Grade 12.

Just being invited to participate in this exhibition is a great honor due to the rigorous adjudication process. Students create these works in their art classes and each school selects 10 artworks to submit. These artworks are then adjudicated at the county level and the finalists' artworks are matted, framed, and exhibited for the public.

These artworks will be judged virtually on May 15 and the winners will be announced on May 18. #VolusiaStudentsCreate

🔗 For more information: https://bit.ly/48thVolusiaStudentsCreate

post_text:
At this time, Volusia County Schools seniors have graduation ceremonies scheduled for May. If these dates have to be canceled due to social distancing orders, we now have confirmed back-up dates for graduations to be held during the week of July 6, 2020.
After consulting with student leadership at our ten high schools and their principals, the overwhelming response was a desire to have a traditional graduation as opposed to alternative venues.
We will continue researching the viability of other senior activities such as yearbook signings, senior breakfast alternatives, college signings, academic and athletic awards ceremonies and will continue communicating with our student government leaders, principals, parents and other stakeholders.

post_text: The Governor issued a statewide stay-at-home order. This limits outside movement to essential services and essential activities. post_text: Census Day is April 1, 2020. Did you know that a big way our community gets money for child and family programs is by participating in the U.S. Census? The state and federal government uses census information to fund programs like child care, free and low-cost school lunches, and healthcare. Responding to the Census helps communities get the funding they need and helps businesses make data-driven decisions that grow the economy. Census data impacts our daily lives, informing important decisions about funding for health care, senior centers, jobs, political representation, roads, schools, and businesses. Everyone must be counted in the census so that these valuable resources aren't lost.

A complete count of every person living in the United States has tremendous benefits for students, staff, and community
members, including:

• Special Education
• School Lunch Assistance
• Teacher Training
• Head Start
• Technology
• After School Programs

Census data is used to determine how much Title I money
schools will get from the government. This means, more money for schools with high numbers of students from low-income families.

Everyone living in your home on April 1st counts on the 2020 Census. You can respond online, by phone or by mail. Go to 2020census.gov for more info.

#2020Census #shapeyourfuturestarthere #everyonecounts

post_text: The Seabreeze High School Vocal Department Choir has been selected to perform at Carnegie Hall, as the featured chorus, during a concert on March 21. To ensure all thirty students get to attend, there will be a community fundraising event at the Hard Rock Hotel on Saturday night, January 18. The band Greye will be playing. post_text:
UPDATE (12:56PM) : THE LOCKDOWN HAS BEEN LIFTED

UPDATE: (12:50PM) : Per the Sheriff's office, the campus has been cleared, with no weapons found, and no one injured in any way. There was no shooting. The lockdown has not been lifted at this time as deputies are continuing to investigate the origin of the apparent false report.

Heritage Middle School is in a lockdown. The sheriff's office received a tip that there could be a weapon on campus. Sheriff's deputies are at the school right now, and no weapon has been found at this time. Also, there has been false information circulating about this event. Please do not share information unless it comes from the school district or VCSO. We will keep you posted. Thank you.
text:
UPDATE (12:56PM) : THE LOCKDOWN HAS BEEN LIFTED

UPDATE: (12:50PM) : Per the Sheriff's office, the campus has been cleared, with no weapons found, and no one injured in any way. There was no shooting. The lockdown has not been lifted at this time as deputies are continuing to investigate the origin of the apparent false report.

Heritage Middle School is in a lockdown. The sheriff's office received a tip that there could be a weapon on campus. Sheriff's deputies are at the school right now, and no weapon has been found at this time. Also, there has been false information circulating about this event. Please do not share information unless it comes from the school district or VCSO. We will keep you posted. Thank you.

post_text:
The AdventHealth Deltona ER Grand Opening was a huge success! Thank you so much to the fantastic health academy volunteers from University, Pine Ridge and Deltona High, to the Deltona High drum line, cheerleaders, and ROTC, and to all of the academy teachers, school administrators, and students who attended the festivities.

We are excited to have such a wonderful new facility available in the community. Additional opportunities for students to tour, job shadow, and intern will continue to enhance students’ career exploration in healthcare. Thank you for taking time out of your evening to share in the excitement.
text:
The AdventHealth Deltona ER Grand Opening was a huge success! Thank you so much to the fantastic health academy volunteers from University, Pine Ridge and Deltona High, to the Deltona High drum line, cheerleaders, and ROTC, and to all of the academy teachers, school administrators, and students who attended the festivities.

We are excited to have such a wonderful new facility available in the community. Additional opportunities for students to tour, job shadow, and intern will continue to enhance students’ career exploration in healthcare. Thank you for taking time out of your evening to share in the excitement.
